    {
      "_id": "083af1a66b38efca",
      "name": "Roll Method",
      "ownership": {
        "default": -1
      },
      "sort": 9,
      "text": {
        "content": "<p id=\"1cf1b90a-e081-813a-8872-c664e0b6b4f9\">You determine your starting values by rolling\n\t\t\t\t<strong>1d6-3</strong> four times, and then assign each value to an Attribute of your choice. You then gain\n\t\t\t\t<strong>+2</strong> Attribute Points to increase whichever Attributes you want, up to the Attribute Limit (3).\n\t\t\t</p><p id=\"1cf1b90a-e081-81d5-8475-caefc3de48c0\"><strong>Prime Modifier\n\t\t\t\t\t\tInsurance:</strong> If the value of your highest Attribute is\n\t\t\t\tless than 3 (even after adding the <strong>+2</strong> Attribute Points), you can reduce a different Attribute\n\t\t\t\tvalue by <strong>1</strong> or more to increase your highest Attribute by the same amount. You can’t reduce an\n\t\t\t\tAttribute value below <strong>-2</strong> or increase an Attribute above your Attribute Limit (3).</p><p id=\"1cf1b90a-e081-81a2-81c9-c9268cad9764\" class=\"block-color-purple_background\"><strong>DC Tip:</strong> This\n\t\t\t\tmethod of determining your starting Attributes is the most risky. It offers the potential for the highest\n\t\t\t\tstarting Attributes, but also the lowest. If you add all your Attributes together, their sum should be 4 (on\n\t\t\t\taverage), after the +2 bonus points are added. If you get less than this, then talk to your GM about potentially\n\t\t\t\trerolling your Attributes (or using a different method).</p>",
        "format": 1
      },
      "title": {
        "level": 3,
        "show": true
      },
      "type": "text",
      "system": {},
      "image": {},
      "video": {
