    {
      "_id": "dabc44b978ca9b16",
      "name": "Prime Modifier Equals Attribute Limit",
      "ownership": {
        "default": -1
      },
      "sort": 16,
      "text": {
        "content": "<p id=\"1cf1b90a-e081-81e5-8716-d1a2586afa0a\">Instead of Prime Modifier being determined by a PCs highest\n\t\t\t\tAttribute, it's instead equal to their Attribute Limit. This means it will always be \"maxed out\",\n\t\t\t\tno matter where you put your Attributes Points. This rule is designed for Players who want to create a PC\n\t\t\t\tthat's more well-rounded and doesn't have one or two main Attributes they lean heavily on. This rule\n\t\t\t\tallows for Players to have more freedom in character creation, because their Prime Modifier will always start at\n\t\t\t\t3 and progress with their level.</p><p id=\"1cf1b90a-e081-81b4-baef-c412c40c5030\" class=\"block-color-purple_background\"><strong>DC Tip: </strong>Be\n\t\t\t\taware that if everyone in the group builds a balanced PC, then no one in the group will be the go to for certain\n\t\t\t\tactivities or skills. This can ruin the nuanced group dynamics that TTRPG parties are often designed around,\n\t\t\t\twhere every PC feels like they have a strong purpose that's supported by mechanical advantages and not just\n\t\t\t\tnarrative choices. If you like to have groups in which each PC gets their moments in the spotlight, then this\n\t\t\t\tmight not be a rule for you.</p>",
        "format": 1
      },
